  "prompt_text": "Derive the quadratic formula from the general form ax^2 + bx + c = 0.",
  "response_text": "To derive the quadratic formula from the general form ax^2 + bx + c = 0, we start by manipulating the equation to isolate the variable x.\n\nFirst, we want to get the x^2 term by itself on one side of the equation. To do this, we can subtract c from both sides of the equation:\n\nax^2 + bx + c = 0\nax^2 + bx = -c\n\nNext, we want to get the x term by itself on one side of the equation. To do this, we can subtract bx from both sides of the equation:\n\nax^2 = -bx - c\n\nNow, we want to get the x term isolated. To do this, we can divide both sides of the equation by a (assuming a is not equal to 0):\n\nx^2 = (-b/a) - (c/a)\n\nNow, we want to get x by itself. To do this, we can take the square root of both sides of the equation:\n\nx = ±√((-b/a) - (c/a))\n\nSimplifying the expression under the square root, we get:\n\nx = ±√((-b ± √(b^2 - 4ac)) / 2a)\n\nThis is the quadratic formula, which can be written more compactly as:\n\nx = (-b ± √(b^2 - 4ac)) / 2a\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 8\nC (Contextual Awareness): 7\nY (Affective Modeling): 4\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 9",
